## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Thread.Abort to Cooperative Cancellation

**Pattern:** Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException as control flow

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is a no-op. The fix is cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`.

### Problems in the Original Code

| API | .NET 8 Behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`) |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | No-op / obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the
            // token fires, even if Task.Run's body doesn't check the token.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Prefer this async overload in new code
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            return await task.WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw; // caller cancelled — propagate as-is
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Work doesn't check the token** | `Task.WaitAsync` lets the *caller* stop waiting, but the delegate keeps running on the thread pool until it finishes naturally. If `work` is a tight CPU loop, pass and check a `CancellationToken` inside it. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Expecting instant termination** | Cooperative cancellation only works at checkpoints. If `work` calls uninterruptible native code, the background task will linger. For truly uncooperative code, move it to a child process and use `Process.Kill`. |

### If `work` Can Cooperate (Best Case)

Change the signature to accept a token so work actually stops:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                   .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                   .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return results;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

This is the only way to guarantee the background work actually stops promptly.
